title: Who wins inaugural season? Ultimate AFLW guide
text:
2 — Kara Donnellan (Fremantle), Emma Kearney (Western Bulldogs) 
1 — Chelsea Randall (Adelaide Crows) 
Best player coming from another sport 
3 — Erin Phillips (Adelaide Crows/basketball). 
1 — Ellie Brush (GWS Giants/soccer), Bree Davey (Carlton/soccer), Gemma Houghton (Fremantle/basketball), Cat Phillips (Melbourne/frisbee), Helen Roden (Collingwood/basketball) 
Leading goalkicker 
2 — Moana Hope (Collingwood) 
1 — Katie Brennan (Western Bulldogs), Mel Caulfield (Fremantle), Ellyse Gamble (Western Bulldogs), Taylor Harris (Brisbane Lions), Sarah Perkins (Adelaide Crows), Darcy Vescio (Carlton) 
Rising Star winner 
2 — Ashley Sharp (Fremantle) 
1 — Nicola Barr (GWS Giants), Deanna Berry (Melbourne), Jasmine Garner (Collingwood), Shaleise Law (Brisbane Lions), Ebony Marinoff (Adelaide Crows), Hayley Miller (Fremantle) The AFLW premiership cup. Picture: Wayne Ludbey Source: News Corp Australia 
PLAYERS TO WATCH 
Adelaide Crows 
Erin Phillips. The two-time Olympic basketballer hasn’t played much footy but should bring plenty of X-factor after stints as a point guard for the Opals and several WNBA teams. Will play mostly as a forward. 
Brisbane Lions 
Tayla Harris. The 19-year-old is renowned for taking spectacular hangers and has a unique kicking style in which her boot winds up almost in line with her head. Expect her to build up an impressive highlights reel. 
Carlton 
Brianna Davey. The former Matildas goalkeeper is no stranger to elite competition, debuting for Melbourne Victory in the W-League at 15 and earning her first international cap a year later. A marquee pick and talented on-baller. 
Collingwood 
Moana Hope. The competition’s most recognisable player, Hope booted six goals in last year’s women’s All-Star game before handing AFL supremo Gillon McLachlan a ‘dabbing’ lesson. No surprise the nation’s biggest sporting team snapped up the tattooed forward. 
Fremantle 
Kara Donnellan. Donnellan’s comparisons to former West Coast and Carlton superstar Chris Judd in the way she plays have ensured plenty of fans will be keen to see the Dockers captain in action. A prolific ball-winner. 
GWS Giants 
Nicola Barr. The No. 1 draft pick is a rising star of the game. A junior soccer player, Barr was late to footy but has developed into an elite midfielder. 
Melbourne 
Daisy Pearce. A gun on-baller, Pearce took out the inaugural VFL women’s best-and-fairest award last year. The former midwife is a leading ambassador for women’s footy and will captain the Demons. 
Western Bulldogs 
Katie Brennan. The athletic key forward booted 150 goals in the past three women’s VFL seasons. 'Monumental moment' for sport
